### Key Insights 1

::: {style="border: 1px solid #ccc; padding: 20px; background-color: #fdfdfd; border-radius: 5px; margin: 20px 0;"}

* China’s **decarbonisation relies heavily on transitioning away from coal**, which is the primary source of CO2 emissions, towards renewables.

* While **solar and wind capacity is expanding rapidly**, coal still makes up a vast majority of energy production. 

* Energy production from coal fell in 2025 for the first time in the last decade, by 70.6 TWh, while solar and wind increased by 335.9 and 138.4 TWh respectively. Combined, solar and wind growth nearly outpaced the total electricity demand growth of 502.7 TWh in 2025.

* The continued **high annual growth of solar energy generation over the last decade** has resulted from **intensive investment in renewable infrastructure**, which has aided in rapid unit cost reductions, as battery and solar photovoltaic costs have fallen by more than 90% since 2015. 

:::

