## Key Takeaway

::: {style="border: 1px solid #ccc; padding: 20px; background-color: #fdfdfd; border-radius: 5px; margin: 20px 0;"}

* Solar energy production has a uniquely **high growth**, yet a **high risk**. 

* **Therefore, higher volatility in solar energy generation necessitates grid firming investments**. 

:::

## Limitations

::: {style="border: 1px solid #ccc; padding: 20px; background-color: #fdfdfd; border-radius: 5px; margin: 20px 0;"}

1. The hypothesis test relied on the **small sample size** (**n = 11**, 2015 to 2025), limiting the validity of normality assumption, potentially skewing variance estimates. 


2. The 2026 Global Electricity Review dataset’s country **aggregate and yearly format limits analysis of energy production, demand, and growth over shorter periods and smaller regions** (inability to indicate high frequency volatility or localised grid stress at the provincial level). 


3. Confounders such as the **COVID-19 pandemic** may have influenced the growth rate of solar photovoltaics by disrupting supply chains and installation capacity, limiting conclusions drawn about individual solar growth volatility. 

:::

# Hypthoesis Testing

## Hypothesis

::: {style="border: 1px solid #ccc; padding: 20px; background-color: #fdfdfd; border-radius: 5px; margin: 20px 0;"}

**Null Hypothesis ($H_0$):**  $\sigma^2_{\text{solar}} = \sigma^2_{\text{coal}}$ 

The variance of annual electricity generation growth rates for solar energy is equal to the variance of annual growth rates for coal baseload. (i.e. both energy sources exhibit the same level of growth stability).
    
**Alternative Hypothesis ($H_1$):**  $\sigma^2_{\text{solar}} > \sigma^2_{\text{coal}}$ 


The variance of annual solar energy growth rates is greater than that of coal baseload, validating the necessity of grid firming solar investments. 
:::


## Assumptions


::: {style="border: 1px solid #ccc; padding: 20px; background-color: #fdfdfd; border-radius: 5px; margin: 20px 0;"}

1. Observations consist of year-on-year annual growth percentages from 2015 to 2025. Annual changes in electricity generation were assumed to act as mutually independent data points over time.

3. Traditional parametric variance testing assumes data is normally distributed. 

```{r}

qq_data = generation_type_1 %>% filter(Variable %in% c("Solar", "Coal"))

ggplot(qq_data, aes(sample = growth_percentage, color = Variable)) +
stat_qq(size = 1.5) +
stat_qq_line(linewidth = 1) +
facet_wrap(~Variable, scales = "free") +
scale_color_manual(values = energy_colours_2) +
theme_minimal() +
labs(title = "Normal Q-Q Plots for Annual Growth Rates", subtitle = "Checking Normality Assumptions for Solar and Coal (2015 - 2025)", x = "Theoretical Quantiles", y = "Sample Quantiles") +
theme(legend.position = "none", strip.text = element_text(face = "bold", size = 11), plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"))

```

Evaluation of the normal Q-Q plots indicates that the internal data points cluster closely along the trendline, except for outer tail points, which diverge slightly from the theoretical diagonals. This supports the assumption that the datasets are approximately normally distributed. 


:::


## Test Statistics and P-Values

### Shapiro-Wilks Test 

::: {style="border: 1px solid #ccc; padding: 5px 20px 20px 20px; background-color: #fdfdfd; border-radius: 5px; margin: 20px 0;"}
```{r}
growth_solar = qq_data %>% filter(Variable == "Solar") %>% pull(growth_percentage)
growth_coal = qq_data %>% filter(Variable == "Coal") %>% pull(growth_percentage)

shapiro_solar = shapiro.test(growth_solar)
shapiro_coal = shapiro.test(growth_coal)

levene_res = leveneTest(growth_percentage ~ Variable, data = qq_data, center = median)
levene_f = round(levene_res$`F value`[1], 3)
levene_p = levene_res$`Pr(>F)`[1]

f_res = var.test(growth_solar, growth_coal, alternative = "greater")
f_value = round(f_res$statistic, 3)
f_p = f_res$p.value

format_p = function(p) {if (p < 0.001) {return(formatC(p, format = "e", digits = 3))} else {return(paste0(round(p, 3)))}}

summary_table = data.frame(`Statistical Test` = c("**Shapiro-Wilk**", "**Shapiro-Wilk**"),`Variable` = c("Solar Growth", "Coal Growth"),`Metric` = c("$W$-statistic", "$W$-statistic"),`Value` = c(round(shapiro_solar$statistic, 3), round(shapiro_coal$statistic, 3)),`P-Value` = c(format_p(shapiro_solar$p.value), format_p(shapiro_coal$p.value)),`Result / Significance` = c("Fail to reject $H_0$ (Normally distributed data)", "Fail to reject $H_0$ (Normally distributed data)"), check.names = FALSE)

kable(summary_table, align = c('l', 'l', 'l', 'c', 'c', 'l'))
```
:::

### Interpretation and Rationale for Alternative Testing 

::: {style="border: 1px solid #ccc; padding: 20px; background-color: #fdfdfd; border-radius: 5px; margin: 20px 0;"}
While the Shapiro-Wilk tests failed to reject the null hypothesis of normality ($p > 0.05$), the low sample size significantly limits the ability to detect true non normality. To mitigate this limitation, a non parametric Levene's Test (centred at the median) was run alongside the main F-test (since it doesn't require or assume normality). 
:::

### F and Levene's Tests

::: {style="border: 1px solid #ccc; padding: 20px; background-color: #fdfdfd; border-radius: 5px; margin: 20px 0;"}

```{r}
summary_table_2 = data.frame(`Statistical Test` = c("**F-Test**", "**Levene’s Test**"),`Variable` = c("Solar vs. Coal", "Solar vs. Coal"),`Metric` = c("$F$-statistic", "$F$-statistic"),`Value` = c(as.numeric(f_value), levene_f),`P-Value` = c(format_p(f_p), format_p(levene_p)),`Result / Significance` = c("**Reject $H_0$ (Solar Variance > Coal)**", "**Reject $H_0$ (Unequal Variances)**"), check.names = FALSE)

kable(summary_table_2)
```

:::


## Conclusion

::: {style="border: 1px solid #ccc; padding: 20px; background-color: #fdfdfd; border-radius: 5px; margin: 20px 0;"}

The parametric $F$-test yielded a test statistic of $F = 27.209$ with an associated p-value of $p = 6.258 \times 10^{-6}$, substantiating the definitive rejection of the null hypothesis ($H_0$). Additionally, parallel validation via the non parametric Levene’s test strongly supported this outcome ($p = 0.003$), as both p values fell far below the significance threshold ($p = 0.05$). Therefore, this proves that the variance of China's annual solar growth is significantly greater than that of coal baseload infrastructure.

These tests confirm that while solar energy capacity is expanding rapidly, its high internal volatility results in severe variable stress on the electrical transmission network. This validates the necessity of transitioning investment toward utility scale grid firming assets, such as rapid response battery storage systems, to insulate network load and maintain stability throughout the ongoing decarbonisation process.

:::



